# Types of SQL Injection
1. In-band SQL Injection
Attacker gets results directly in the application response
2. Blind SQL Injection
No visible error messages
Attacker infers data through true/false responses
3. Error-based SQL Injection
Uses database error messages to extract information

# Prevention Methods
1. Parameterized Queries (Best Practice)
Separates SQL code from user input
Prevents input from being executed as SQL
2. Input Validation
Restricting expected input types and formats
3. Least Privilege Database Accounts
Limits damage if an injection occurs
4. Web Application Firewalls (WAF)
Helps detect and block malicious input patterns

# Why SQL Injection is Dangerous
Can expose sensitive user data
Can lead to full database compromise
One of the most common web vulnerabilities (OWASP Top 10)

